  "prompt": "Why do Navy squadrons start with a V?",
  "response": "U.S. Navy squadron designations starting with \"V\" indicate squadrons that fly **fixed-wing aircraft**. This is a convention used to quickly identify the type of aircraft operated by a particular unit.\n\nHere's a more detailed breakdown:\n\n*   **V - Fixed-wing:** Generally signifies fixed-wing aircraft (airplanes)\n*   The second letter denotes the mission or type of aircraft:\n    *   A - Attack\n    *   F - Fighter\n    *   Q - Electronic Warfare\n    *   W - Early Warning\n    *   P - Maritime Patrol\n    *   C - Fleet Logistics Support\n    *   R - Reconnaissance\n    *   T - Training\n\n**Examples:**\n\n*   **VA** - Attack Squadron (flies attack aircraft like the F/A-18E/F Super Hornet in an attack role)\n*   **VF** - Fighter Squadron (flies fighter aircraft like the F/A-18E/F Super Hornet in a fighter role)\n*   **VP** - Patrol Squadron (flies maritime patrol aircraft like the P-8 Poseidon)\n*   **VQ** - Electronic Warfare Squadron (flies electronic warfare aircraft)\n*   **VR** - Fleet Logistics Support Squadron (flies transport aircraft)\n\n**Important Note:**\n\n*   Helicopter squadrons use \"H\" at the start of their designation.\n*   This is a general rule, and there can be occasional exceptions or changes over time as roles and aircraft evolve.\n\nSo, in summary, the \"V\" in Navy squadron designations signifies that the unit operates **fixed-wing aircraft**.\n",
